         <fn id="d5308e203a1310">
            <label>2</label>
            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d5308e210" publication-type="book">
Phaedrus begins with Socrates drawing attention to the speech
of Lysias that Phaedrus holds in his left hand. In a detail neither more nor less coin-
cidental, Zen begins on the same side: "I can see by my watch, without taking my
hand from the left grip of the cycle, that it is eight-thirty in the morning" (3).  <fpage>3</fpage>
               </mixed-citation>
            </p>
